<body>

  <div class=3D"title-block">
    <h1>Binance Gold &amp; Silver Perpetuals and ETF Markets</h1>
    <p class=3D"sub">Event study: impact on volatility, liquidity, and inte=
gration</p>
    <p class=3D"meta">KSE Python course project</p>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> Introduce the proj=
ect in one sentence: we ask whether the launch of Binance TRADFI gold and s=
ilver perpetuals changed how the established ETF markets (GLD, SLV) behave.=
 Mention event date: 2026-01-05.</div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>1. Research question</h1>
    <p><strong>Did the introduction of Binance TRADFI gold and silver perpe=
tual futures (XAUUSDT, XAGUSDT) change:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Volatility</strong> of gold and silver ETFs (GLD, SLV)</l=
i>
      <li><strong>Liquidity</strong> (volume, Amihud illiquidity)</li>
      <li><strong>Price integration</strong> (correlation ETF=E2=80=93perpe=
tual): we <em>have</em> data <strong>after</strong> the launch (rolling cor=
relation GLD=E2=80=93XAU, SLV=E2=80=93XAG); we do <strong>not</strong> have=
 pre-event integration (Binance did not exist), so we describe post-event i=
ntegration only, not a pre/post test.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Event: launch date <strong>2026-01-05</strong>.</p>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> State the research=
 question. For integration, clarify: we have correlation data only post-eve=
nt; we describe how strong integration is after the launch, but we cannot t=
est =E2=80=9Cintegration increased=E2=80=9D because there is no pre-period =
for Binance.</div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>2. Why this story matters</h1>
    <p>Gold and silver are traded as <strong>ETFs</strong> (GLD, SLV) on re=
gulated exchanges. In early 2026, Binance started listing <strong>perpetual=
s</strong> on the same assets (XAUUSDT, XAGUSDT). So now there are <strong>=
two places</strong> to get exposure to the same thing.</p>
    <p>We ask: did the <strong>ETF market change</strong> after that? More =
volatile? More trading? More linked to the new venue? This matters for trad=
ers, market-makers, and regulators.</p>
    <img src=3D"file:///Users/nz3000/Python/Gold_Project/presentation_figur=
es/why_story_two_venues.png" alt=3D"Before: one venue; After: two venues" c=
lass=3D"chart" width=3D"700">
    <div class=3D"placeholder" style=3D"display:none;">Run <code>python3 ex=
port_presentation_data.py</code> to generate figures.</div>
    <blockquote class=3D"lit">"The introduction of derivatives can change s=
pot markets=E2=80=94volatility, liquidity, and how prices move together."<b=
r><cite>Augustin, Rubtsov &amp; Shin (2023), Management Science =E2=80=94 B=
itcoin futures and spot markets.</cite></blockquote>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> Tell the story: tw=
o venues, same asset. Our question is not only =E2=80=9Cdid volatility go u=
p?=E2=80=9D but =E2=80=9Chow did the structure of trading change?=E2=80=9D<=
/div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>3. Data: sources and periods</h1>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Source</th>
          <th>What we get</th>
          <th>Frequency</th>
          <th>Rows</th>
          <th>Note</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Binance API</strong></td>
          <td>XAUUSDT, XAGUSDT (OHLCV), funding, OI (TRADIFI_PERPETUAL)</td=
>
          <td>1m</td>
          <td>67k+</td>
          <td>From 2026-01-05 (XAU), 2026-01-07 (XAG)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Yahoo Finance</strong></td>
          <td>ETFs: GLD, SLV, IAU, GDX, SIL. Controls: DXY, VIX, TNX. GLD/S=
LV 1m</td>
          <td>Daily; 1m last 7d</td>
          <td>118 daily; 1m limited</td>
          <td>1m only last ~7 days</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>FRED</strong></td>
          <td>DGS10 =E2=80=94 10Y Treasury rate (macro control)</td>
          <td>Daily</td>
          <td>in daily panel</td>
          <td>Same role as TNX, from Fed data</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p><strong>Panels:</strong> Daily =3D 118 rows (event study, OLS). 1-mi=
nute =3D 67k+ rows (intraday analysis). <strong>Integration:</strong> post-=
event only (rolling corr, beta; no Binance before 2026-01-05).</p>
    <p><em>DXY</em> =3D dollar index; <em>VIX</em> =3D volatility index; <e=
m>TNX</em> / <em>DGS10</em> =3D 10Y yield (Yahoo / FRED). Used as controls.=
</p>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> One table, row cou=
nts clear. Panels and integration in one line. FRED DGS10 =3D 10Y rate from=
 Fed.</div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>4. How we use the data</h1>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Daily panel</strong> (features_daily.csv): 118 days =C3=
=97 87 variables. Used for event study=E2=80=94pre/post means, t-tests, OLS=
 with <code>post_event</code> and controls (DXY, VIX, 10Y).</li>
      <li><strong>1-minute panel</strong> (features_1m.csv): one row per Bi=
nance XAUUSDT 1m candle, daily ETF/controls merged by date. We use it for i=
ntraday return distribution and daily realized vol from 1m.</li>
      <li><strong>Minute-level correlation</strong>: last 7 days where Yaho=
o 1m (GLD/SLV) overlaps with Binance 1m=E2=80=94we compute same-frequency c=
orrelation GLD=E2=80=93XAU, SLV=E2=80=93XAG (another integration metric, po=
st-event only).</li>
      <li><strong>Integration (descriptive)</strong>: rolling correlation a=
nd beta in the daily panel and in the key-results table; we report post-eve=
nt level and evolution only (no pre/post test for integration).</li>
    </ul>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> Daily for regressi=
ons and tests; 1m for scale and minute correlation. Integration: we use the=
 data to describe how strong the link is after the launch, not to test a ch=
ange.</div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>5. Event and method</h1>
    <img src=3D"file:///Users/nz3000/Python/Gold_Project/presentation_figur=
es/event_method_design.png" alt=3D"Event study design: timeline and OLS" cl=
ass=3D"chart" width=3D"700">
    <div class=3D"placeholder" style=3D"display:none;">Run <code>python3 ex=
port_presentation_data.py</code> to generate figures.</div>
    <p><strong>Design:</strong> Event study with pre/post comparison. No co=
ntrol group =E2=86=92 we do <strong>not</strong> use difference-in-differen=
ces.</p>
    <p><strong>Tests:</strong> (1) Welch t-tests (pre vs post); (2) OLS wit=
h outcome =3D volatility or liquidity, regressor =3D <code>post_event</code=
> + <strong>controls (DXY, VIX, 10Y)</strong>. HAC (Newey=E2=80=93West) SE;=
 winsorization 5%/95%.</p>
    <p><strong>Why controls?</strong> DXY (dollar), VIX (volatility index),=
 10Y yield (Yahoo TNX / FRED DGS10) capture general market conditions. By i=
ncluding them in OLS, the coefficient on <code>post_event</code> measures t=
he effect of <strong>the listing itself</strong>, not just =E2=80=9Cthe mar=
ket moved=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94so we can argue that the change in ETF volatilit=
y/volume is due to the Binance launch, not confounded by macro.</p>
    <p class=3D"ref"><strong>Literature:</strong> Augustin et al. (2023), M=
anagement Science =E2=80=94 impact of Bitcoin futures on spot; they use DiD=
 with treatment/control. We have a single market before/after, so we use pr=
e/post + OLS with controls. See Literature/LITERATURE_METHODS.md.</p>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> Use the figure: ti=
meline shows one market, pre and post; the OLS box shows we estimate the ef=
fect of the event (=CE=B2) controlling for macro. Mention that the Bitcoin =
futures paper uses DiD; we cannot because we have no control group.</div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>6. Cumulative returns (ETFs vs Binance)</h1>
    <img src=3D"file:///Users/nz3000/Python/Gold_Project/presentation_figur=
es/cumulative_returns.png" alt=3D"Cumulative returns index 100" class=3D"ch=
art" width=3D"900">
    <div class=3D"placeholder" style=3D"display:none;">Run <code>python3 ex=
port_presentation_data.py</code> to generate figures.</div>
    <p>On the chart, <strong>higher line =3D higher cumulative return</stro=
ng>: silver (SLV, XAGUSDT) outperforms gold (GLD, XAUUSDT) in this sample. =
<strong>After the event</strong>, all four series move together=E2=80=94tha=
t co-movement is the first visual evidence of integration between ETF and B=
inance markets.</p>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> Explain: higher li=
ne means more profitable. Silver lines sit above gold in this period. The m=
ain takeaway for our story: once Binance launches, all four lines move in s=
ync=E2=80=94integration.</div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>7. Volatility and volume over time</h1>
    <img src=3D"file:///Users/nz3000/Python/Gold_Project/presentation_figur=
es/vol_volume.png" alt=3D"Volatility and volume" class=3D"chart" width=3D"9=
00">
    <div class=3D"placeholder" style=3D"display:none;">Run <code>python3 ex=
port_presentation_data.py</code> to generate figures.</div>
    <p>Volatility and volume dynamics around the event=E2=80=94basis for H1=
 and H2. <strong>Silver (SLV) reacts more strongly:</strong> post-event, bo=
th realized and Parkinson volatility, and ETF volume, rise more for SLV tha=
n for GLD.</p>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> Point to the red l=
ine: after the event, all three panels jump, but silver (grey line) jumps m=
ore=E2=80=94higher volatility and a big volume spike. This motivates testin=
g whether the effect is significant (next slide) and robust to controls.</d=
iv>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>8. Pre vs post: how much did each metric grow?</h1>
    <img src=3D"file:///Users/nz3000/Python/Gold_Project/presentation_figur=
es/pre_post_bars.png" alt=3D"Pre vs post % change" class=3D"chart" width=3D=
"900">
    <div class=3D"placeholder" style=3D"display:none;">Run <code>python3 ex=
port_presentation_data.py</code> to generate figures.</div>
    <p><strong>One chart, one message:</strong> after the event, volatility=
 and volume increase (positive %); <strong>silver (SLV) increases more than=
 gold (GLD)</strong>. Same units (%) make the comparison clear. Below we te=
st whether these changes are statistically significant (t-test) and then co=
ntrol for macro in regressions.</p>
    <p><strong>T-test:</strong> For each metric we test H=E2=82=80: mean(po=
st) =3D mean(pre) with a <strong>two-sample Welch t-test</strong> (unequal =
variances): we take all pre-event days and all post-event days, compute the=
 two means, and the test gives us <strong>t</strong> (how many standard err=
ors the difference is) and <strong>p</strong> (probability of such a differ=
ence under H=E2=82=80). Low p (e.g. p &lt; 0.05) =E2=86=92 reject H=E2=82=
=80 =E2=86=92 change is significant. Shown as <code>&lt;0.001</code> when p=
 is below 0.001.</p>
    <div id=3D"slide8-ttest-container"><table><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th=
>Pre mean</th><th>Post mean</th><th>Pct</th><th>t</th><th>t-test p</th></tr=
></thead><tbody><tr><td>GLD 20d vol</td><td>0.013439</td><td>0.024582</td><=
td>+83%</td><td>5.809</td><td>&lt;0.001</td></tr><tr><td>SLV 20d vol</td><t=
d>0.024114</td><td>0.068572</td><td>+184%</td><td>9.492</td><td>&lt;0.001</=
td></tr><tr><td>GLD volume</td><td>15.123725</td><td>22.480038</td><td>+49%=
</td><td>2.377</td><td>0.0222</td></tr><tr><td>SLV volume</td><td>43.889215=
</td><td>140.791356</td><td>+221%</td><td>5.913</td><td>&lt;0.001</td></tr>=
</tbody></table></div>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> =E2=80=9CHorizonta=
l bars =3D % change post vs pre. All four go up; the two SLV bars are longe=
r=E2=80=94silver reacted more. The table shows t-test p-values: small p mea=
ns the pre=E2=86=92post change is significant. We then control for macro in=
 regressions.=E2=80=9D</div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>9. Correlation matrix (key variables)</h1>
    <img src=3D"file:///Users/nz3000/Python/Gold_Project/presentation_figur=
es/correlation_matrix.png" alt=3D"Correlation matrix" class=3D"chart" width=
=3D"900">
    <div class=3D"placeholder" style=3D"display:none;">Run <code>python3 ex=
port_presentation_data.py</code> to generate figures.</div>
    <p><strong>What it shows:</strong> Pairwise correlations between the ma=
in variables we use: ETF returns (GLD, SLV), Binance perpetual returns (XAU=
, XAG), macro controls (DXY, VIX, 10Y/TNX), and realized volatility (GLD 20=
d, SLV 20d). Red =3D positive, blue =3D negative. High correlation between =
GLD and XAU (and SLV and XAG) in the post-event overlap supports integratio=
n; macro variables help us control for common factors in regressions.</p>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> =E2=80=9CCorrelati=
on matrix of our key variables. ETF=E2=80=93Binance return pairs are highly=
 correlated where we have data; we use DXY, VIX, rates as controls.=E2=80=
=9D</div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>10. Integration: do ETF and Binance perpetual move together?</h1>
    <img src=3D"file:///Users/nz3000/Python/Gold_Project/presentation_figur=
es/rolling_corr.png" alt=3D"Rolling 20d correlation" class=3D"chart" width=
=3D"900">
    <div class=3D"placeholder" style=3D"display:none;">Run <code>python3 ex=
port_presentation_data.py</code> to generate figures.</div>
    <p><strong>What the chart shows:</strong> Rolling 20=E2=80=91day correl=
ation between ETF returns and Binance perpetual returns (GLD=E2=80=93XAU, S=
LV=E2=80=93XAG). We have data only after the launch; the first point appear=
s =E2=89=8820 trading days after the event (rolling window needs 20 days). =
<strong>Values near 0.9=E2=80=931.0</strong> mean the two venues move in lo=
ckstep =E2=86=92 one price-discovery process, arbitrage and hedging link th=
em. We cannot test =E2=80=9Cintegration increased=E2=80=9D because we have =
no pre-event Binance data; we describe the post-event level.</p>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> =E2=80=9CCorrelati=
on is high and stable after launch=E2=80=94ETF and Binance perpetual are in=
tegrated. The chart starts where data exists; we don=E2=80=99t have integra=
tion data before the event.=E2=80=9D</div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>11. Regression results</h1>
    <p><strong>Key result:</strong> Positive and significant coefficient on=
 <code>post_event</code> in volatility regressions (GLD and SLV) <strong>wh=
en we control for DXY, VIX, 10Y</strong> (from Yahoo and FRED) =E2=86=92 <s=
trong>H1 supported</strong>. So the rise in volatility is attributed to the=
 listing, not to general market moves. Volume higher post-event =E2=86=92 <=
strong>H2 supported</strong> (direction). The table includes <strong>Corr G=
LD=E2=80=93XAU</strong> and <strong>Corr SLV=E2=80=93XAG</strong>: post-eve=
nt means only (Pre =3D =E2=80=94); that is our price-integration data.</p>
    <div id=3D"key-results-container"><table><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>=
Pre mean</th><th>Post mean</th><th>Pct</th><th>t</th><th>t-test p</th><th>p=
ost coef</th><th>reg p</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>GLD 20d vol</td><td>=
0.013439</td><td>0.024582</td><td>+83%</td><td>5.809</td><td>&lt;0.001</td>=
<td>0.011</td><td>0.008</td></tr><tr><td>SLV 20d vol</td><td>0.024114</td><=
td>0.068572</td><td>+184%</td><td>9.492</td><td>&lt;0.001</td><td>0.0435</t=
d><td>0</td></tr><tr><td>GLD volume</td><td>15.123725</td><td>22.480038</td=
><td>+49%</td><td>2.377</td><td>0.0222</td><td>=E2=80=94</td><td>=E2=80=94<=
/td></tr><tr><td>SLV volume</td><td>43.889215</td><td>140.791356</td><td>+2=
21%</td><td>5.913</td><td>&lt;0.001</td><td>=E2=80=94</td><td>=E2=80=94</td=
></tr><tr><td>Corr GLD=E2=80=93XAU</td><td>=E2=80=94</td><td>0.918119</td><=
td>=E2=80=94</td><td>=E2=80=94</td><td>=E2=80=94</td><td>=E2=80=94</td><td>=
=E2=80=94</td></tr><tr><td>Corr SLV=E2=80=93XAG</td><td>=E2=80=94</td><td>0=
.934662</td><td>=E2=80=94</td><td>=E2=80=94</td><td>=E2=80=94</td><td>=E2=
=80=94</td><td>=E2=80=94</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
    <p><strong>Insight:</strong> Higher ETF volatility need not mean =E2=80=
=9Cchaos=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94it can reflect more hedging and informed trading =
across the two venues.</p>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> Emphasize: we cont=
rol for macro; the post_event effect is the causal interpretation. Mention =
the non-obvious reading of volatility (hedging/informed flow).</div>
  </div>

  <div class=3D"section">
    <h1>12. Conclusions</h1>
    <p><strong>In short:</strong> The listing of Binance gold/silver perpet=
uals is associated with higher ETF volatility and volume (H1, H2 supported =
when we control for macro). The two venues move together after the launch=
=E2=80=94integration is high where we can measure it. So new derivatives on=
 a new venue can shift incumbent markets; the story is similar to Bitcoin f=
utures (Augustin et al.).</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Findings:</strong> Volatility and volume up post-event (t=
-tests and OLS with DXY, VIX, 10Y). Rolling correlation GLD=E2=80=93XAU, SL=
V=E2=80=93XAG high after launch.</li>
      <li><strong>Who cares:</strong> ETF market-makers, arbitrageurs, regu=
lators=E2=80=94two venues, one price-discovery process.</li>
      <li><strong>Limitations:</strong> No pre-event Binance data (no =E2=
=80=9Cintegration increased=E2=80=9D test); no control group (no DiD); shor=
t post window=E2=80=94more data would help.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class=3D"notes"><strong>Speaker notes:</strong> One slide: what we=
 found, why it matters, what we couldn=E2=80=99t do. Thank the audience and=
 open for questions.</div>
  </div>

